,Not Recommended,318220,20294956,"Posted: 4 January, 2016",all,Cyotey,"DevelopersBefore I go into my review I need to tell you all some things. To put this in the nicest way possible, the developers are an unprofessional, and hypocritical team of failures. If you go into the forums or look at their facebook page you will notice that any negativity against them will result in a ""professional"" and instant lash towards you. In the community forums you will notice that they have whined about negativity towards their ""finished game"". You will also notice that they say they will listen and answer everyone who has a question. I have asked a couple of questions and got no answers from the developers. Only answers from other community members telling me that they do not answer anyone. This game has been abandoned for quite some time and left with bugs and barely any gameplay to justify the price. As far as we're all concerned, they're back to just fix the bugs, add a ""sandbox"" mode and then throw their hands up and be done with it.  I have been banned from the forums yesterday after talking about a promising sounding new police simulator called 'Police 10-13'. Apparently they can't answer questions, but do visit the forums frequently to find an excuse to ban people that don't hold their game in high regards. To be fair, part of what I talked about was how the developers making 10-13 are making themselves look and I quote ""like idiots"" because there are multiple things they are doing that professionals wouldn't do. And the ban is fair according to the rules. In short, I'm iffy about it like I should be after this farce. Only time will tell and I am still excited to see the news and its development.With this said about the developers, please be very cautious about their new project 'CTU' (Counter Terrorism Unit). These developers are childish and are untrustworthy.StoryThe only story there is is a quick intro scene saying that your father was great at being a police officer. After that you're thrown in with a pop up text tutorial and you figure out the rest.GameplayWhile it's clearly clunky and buggy, it is fun for a while. I put in 8 hours before getting very bored. I went back into the game to see if anything was changed or added despite what people said just to make sure, and nothing has been done. All there is is just a few cars you unlock by entering 'codes'. Your duties will differ. You will give chase on foot, get into gunfights, set up speedometers, arrest drunks and those that have harmed others and sometimes break and enter homes that have been reported to have someone armed and dangerous. It's realistic to a very small degree and has potential. Before the game was released, it had a different name and had a lot more going in (more buildings, looked much more polished, basically everything that makes a game look good to hype it up in the beginning). If all that was there it would be really good.SoundVoice acting is terrible, music is very dull and on repeat, guns don't sound right etc. The sound isn't terrible, but it isn't good. And all of the talking past the introduction is silent and through text.GraphicsThe graphics are basically a more polished GTA: San Andreas. Lighting is better and textures are smoother but not by much. It looks like one of the later PS2 games.OverallIt's good in short bursts if you don't care for too much content but the bugs will irritate you enough to not want to play. With Police 10-13 planning on coming sometime in 2016 I would hold off. And there are other simulators much better than this one. The GTA IV police mod is the best one and there's an older and sillier simulation that feels complete as well called Police Force if you don't want to wait. But this ""simulator"" is worth $5 at best and even real police officers are voicing how bad this is. Get a better simulator or hold off for Police 10-13.Small Immediate EditI've had this review written out for quite some time and could not post it up until now and have no idea why and so I saved it and waited. Now that I've finally been able to post it, please spread the word about not getting this game at any price. I have never fallen victim to bad developers as I'm usually good about asking for opinions and looking at whether the business is professional as well up until now. And again, it isn't because I was banned from the forums. I have nothing personal against that. Just their empty promises, lack of news and refusal to keep an open mind and accept the fact that not everyone will be happy and they screwed up badly is why I am bashing them directly. I hope my review helps and happy gaming!"
,Not Recommended,318220,32145351,Posted: 2 June,all,Flowerhorse,"TL;DR: Remember Spacebase DF-9? Pretty much the same thing here. The game is badly optimized, blatantly unfinished, and the developers have abandoned it completely. It is not worth its full price, and I cannot recommend it.---Alright, I've tried to stave off writing this review for roughly a year and a half, in hopes the developers would fix the game's bugs (which, in my opinion, should have been done before full release) and work towards giving us more content. Unfortunately, it seems they have abandoned the game, hence the missing blog page,steamdb pageanddead facebook page.I will attempt to write a 'fair' review, however.Pros-Despite the warnings, you can stay on duty forever. I've found that stress and sleep affect nothing, just make sure your hunger bar doesn't drop too low or your officer will stand still and pant for a few seconds.-You are able to choose between seven different police vehicles, and you can customize them (albeit the customization is lacking).-You have four vehicles available to purchase for driving while off-duty to avoid the great sin of driving your police vehicle while off-duty despite being the only officer in the city.-To drive off the monotony of pulling over impaired and speeding drivers and ticketing cars for parking violations, you can receive calls from dispatch and either accept or refuse them. They give you a reason to use the siren, at least.-Technically, the game delivered on everything it stated in its 'features', barring the amount of missions.Cons-None ofyourvehicles are roadworthy. It takes a second or two for the wheels to straighten after fully turning, and for some reason your vehicle engages the warp drive when accelerating above 30 miles per hour. Additionally, the officer physically cannot depress the brake pedal fully, and holding it down for too long, despite still moving forward, will shift the car into reverse and hit the gas.-The vehicle physics are horrible. Upon colliding with an object, be it a building or a car, no speed will be lost. This can lead to multiple additional collisions as your officer attempts to slow down with the defective brake pedal. The vehicles can climb close to 90 degree slopes, though, so great job to the manufacturers there.-Nobody knows how to drive. None of the drivers in town can maintain their lanes while making a turn. Additionally, there is a loop near the city where a traffic jam will form every day either because a semi cannot make the left turn into the city without hitting a traffic light, or two drivers collide and, due to the collective inability to reverse, are forever stuck. Any driver you pull over will make two consecutive near 90 degree turns while slamming on the brakes, most of the time leading you to either ramming them or passing them. Fleeing drivers will also slam on the brakes after you collide three times, causing the same problem.-The pathfinding (or lack thereof) is terrible. The pedestrians in the game are on rails, which often lead them directly into parked cars or a building. Fleeing suspects will proceed directly away from the player on the nearest rail, or to the nearest rail if not already on a rail. This can lead them to shooting directly up a mountain, as, like in vehicles, forward speed is never decreased. Movement can only be blocked by vehicles and buildings.-Fleeing suspects are a nuisance. Fleeing vehicles usually lead to high damage to your police vehicle. Fleeing suspects run at the same speed or faster than your officer, making chasing them on foot rarely worth it. In addition...-Your officer forgets how to run. When pulling out any of their equipment, your officer will revert back to walking speed. In addition, your officer will only make a brisk jog at max when aiming their weapon, leading to great difficulty when attempting to tase a fleeing suspect.-Sometimes, after going off duty and returning to duty, the dispatcher decides to quit, and you will no longer receive any calls.-Weather and tire smoke tanks your FPS.-Many police vehicles have clipping issues with both your officer and any arrested suspect.-Some zones don't have gas stations.There are probably many more cons I could list here, but it's 2:05 in the morning and I'm too tired to think of anything else the developers left broken or unfinished.If you do insist on buying this game, however, let me make a few recommendations:-Play on realistic mode. You can be given up to three calls at a time, so it gives you stuff to do. The permadeath really doesn't matter.-Don't worry about your reputation. The game only ends if you manage to get -1000. So feel free to uphold the law differently.-The SMG keeps you alive a lot better than the pistol.-Suburbs usually gives you drug-related or burglary calls. Lake usually gives you assault or kidnapping calls. The rest are fairly balanced.So yeah. That's my review. I'm going to go pass out in a pile of blankets now."
