76561198122248263,Not Recommended,318220,16489066,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,I AM THE LIQUOR,"I regret having to give this game a thumbs down, because I really do think it could have been something. In it's current state, it isn't worth the $20 price tag. The game lacks content and gets boring real fast. At this moment, there is only ONE developer working on this game. In the discussion threads, the developer explains that to him, this game is complete, and basically everything from now on is just icing on the cake...WOW... This game is basically an alpha...if that. I understand the whole small team, low budget thing, but to say this game is, in any way complete, is just plain crazy.PROS:+Can be entertaining in small bursts.+Sandbox+The game does have potential (maybe not anymore, but it did).+It has an aspect of realism to it.+The updates are free (as they should be), and the developer stated he didn't want DLCs.+Developers respond to you if you ask a question or comment on something.+Pretty cool customization of your police unit. You can also purchase things like a new flatscreen or a couch for your house with your hard earned cash, which is sweet.CONS:-Bugs/Glitches (apparently not enough to be game breaking as the game is completed--spoken by developer)-Stiff movement system for driving and on-foot. Frustrating controls.-Poor animations.-GTA 3 graphics.-Not enough content to warrant a $20 price tag. It needs more missions/guns/cars/skins/buildings/everything.I really wish this game had more fans and a workshop, because that would change things. More content, better graphics/animations, more skins/customization, would add to the longevity of the game. At the state that this game is in, I cannot recommend this title.Verdict: 5/10"
76561198059593096,Recommended,318220,12672517,"Posted: 28 October, 2014",all,Jaek,"This is clearly a game with a relitively low budget, but still is a very fun police simulator and, in my opinion, worth the money. In this review I will assess the positives and negatives, explain some of the features and finally give my verdict on the game.Positives:- Variety of different missions (passive and direct).- 7 regions to explore.- On and Off Duty modes.- Level up / Ranking system in the police force.- Can interact with every NPC civilian.- Police cars have warning sirens, full sirens, and lightbars that can be customised.- Variety of clothing and vehicle paintjobs.- Realistic feel of policing.- Can storm buildings, make civilians surrender, stop fleeing vehicles by hitting them with yours.- Has an easy and hard mode.Negatives:- At the time of its release, it is quite buggy.- When an ambulance / police transport / tow truck is called, they are not actually seen.- Car physics are not very realistic.- You get reduced career points for actions such as breaking down doors even if there is a criminal inside.- You are the only patrol officer in the game.- Fleeing NPCs act as if they were not being chased if they get clear of you a few metres, then run again when you get close.- Limited things to do Off Duty.- Does not have a very comrehensive help / controls screen.PLEASE NOTE MANY OF THE ABOVE WILL MOST LIKELY BE IMPROVED / FIXED AS THE GAME DEVELOPS!Suggestions:- Could have custom loadouts (e.g. different weapons).- Could call backup such as a SWAT team.- When the player reaches a high rank, they could command other officers.- Needs more vehicles and Off Duty activities (could maybe respond to specific emergencies).Analysis:I am someone who is a big fan of police simulators. Arma 3 Altis Life was great for this, and Enforcer: Police Crime Action is quite similar, only it is single player. You can drive around the town centre looking out for speeders (cars drive around 20mph and around 30mph is considered speeding) and you can pull them over, use the breathalyser or frisk them if you feel it is necessary. On the start of every shift there is a passive mission to complete by the end of the shift, for example setting up a roadblock with cones and checking 6 drivers for faults on their cars. There are also dispatch calls with generous time limits such as finding a person wanted for assaulting passers by. For this you would go and talk to the victims to get a description, then wait until there is intel about where the person was last seen. You would then go to the scene, find the person matching the description, and park up. Normally when you call out for them to stop, they will run off. You can pull out your tazer, and when you get close you fire. After that you can arrest the suspect, take them to the station or call for a transport. You get career points which help you rank up after completing every mission.Off duty mode is really unique, and has a lot of potential. When you have enough money you can buy a car, and you can also customise your home with new furniture. It is also possible to level up your stress level buy going out with friends or your mother, and other people. Instead of actually interacting with your friends or mother, the game teleports you to their house and puts the time forward a few hours, and says that you have spent time with your friends / mother, without you actually seeing anything. Physically doing activities may well be something the developers add in the future. When off duty it is also possible to fill up on food and replenish your energy by sleeping. You have to be careful though as spending too much time off duty will reduce career points.Conclusion:This game as mentioned earlier has obviously been developed on a low budget, but they have made that budget stretch as far as possible. The gameplay is enjoyable even though the graphics and physics are not fantastic. Now it has been released, it is likely that if lots of people buy it and the developers have access to more money, the game will be better optimized, feel more smooth and have some great new features added. That will of course come over time so if anything, the money you put in to buy this game will be an investment, so they can improve it. That said, even before the game is developed further it is still great fun and I can see a lot of hours of gameplay from it.Overall Verdict:I would recommend this game to any fan of police simulators, or anyone who fancies a go at being a police officer. It may at first seem very rough and strange, but believe me, you will probably get used to it just fine.I rate Enforcer: Police Crime Action 7/10 at its current state but it has the potential of being a 8/10 or even 9/10 game.UPDATE: It is now August 2016 with very little development since the review, sadly I would not recommend the game any more."
76561197985169161,Not Recommended,318220,15246990,"Posted: 7 April, 2015",all,rilzi,"Great idea, poor execution. An open world sandbox police 'sim' is something i've wanted to play since the likes of Police Quest. And this game pretty much has that idea down. Unfortunately, it's let down by its execution. The graphics and animation are poor, worse than GTA 3. The AI is all but non existant. All NPC criminals either run from you, give up, or stand in one spot and slowly shoot at you. Pathfinding is poor - pedestrians will mindlessly walk into anything blocking their path forever. The physics are poor. Cars don't crash so much as 'stop'. Hitting a tree, building, or even a pedestrian will cause your car to stop on a dime. Other vehicles also have a tendency to fly into the air randomly.If this was early access, I'd say wait and see, but as a fully released title? Sorry, can't reccomend it especially for the price they're asking."
,Recommended,318220,13367761,"Posted: 14 December, 2014",all,JohnDoe,"This game at it's current form demands a lot of patience from the person that plays it. Most of the AI is very underdeveloped: pedestrians walking everywhere, stoping for nothing and nobody. The driving in the game is a nightmare. Speed is a relative term at the moment, getting from 20mph to 134mph under a second... and good luck stoping... without immidiate reversing. Missions are quite repetative but so is the life of a police officer... as I would imagine.The time passes real quick. An hour in the game equals to a minute in our life not leaving much space to complete missons without doing 16 hours shifts. The concept of getting hungry, tired and irritated is a great idea, but at the moment they don't have much effect on our character. Ranking up is also a great idea... yet again, doesn't really change much. You are still putting those speeding cameras out, regardless your rank. But enough of the negatives.It's a police simulator! Yes. You are wearing a uniform, you have your police cruiser, which is by the way very nicely detailed, as far as sound and lights go. The weapon mechanics is acceptable and it is fun giving out those tickets for broken lights or  speeding thorugh town to attend a burglary.The developers have a great vision. There is no doubt about it. This game might have been released just a bit too early, but their presence in forums and announcments on up-coming updates is reassuring that buying this game at this price is an investment. Now it is up to us if we are willing to invest and see the development through. I am, because it's exciting to be part of developing a great police simulator."
