76561198000510670,Recommended,318220,24946855,"Posted: 15 August, 2016",all,metl,"It's really not that bad. Let's just get that out of the way. Now, on to the review.This game needs some tlc for sure. The car physics aren't that great. They work, but don't expect GTA or Forza handling.The interface suffers from some flaws such as some wonky dialog boxes to choose actions, some odd ""loading"" type screens when taking certain actions that remove a car or an object from the world (such as towing a car or calling an ambulance) and interfacing with cars, drivers and suspects lacks useful feedback beyond a text message at the top of the screen. Some visual feedback would be nice, such as seeing missing/expired plates and/or defective equipment on the cars prior to a dialog-box based inspection once the car is stopped. It's a usuable system, but a complete overhaul to make it more intuitive and user-friendly would be a welcome change.The career system is lacking. I've yet to see any difference in the ""ranks"" beyond unlocking a new vehicle type. It would be nice to see it fleshed out more. Having to go ""off duty"" to reduce your stress level is an interesting idea, but lacks any depth beyond refilling a meter. Some more direct interaction would help it. The station serves little purpose except to drop off prisoners and request a ""warrant"" but I have yet to figure out what that even does.There's a currency in the game which is earned by working and can be spent on furnishing for your home (again, not a bad idea, just needs some work to makeit interesting.) Beyond appearances, everything seems to give the same stat boosts. Take the TV for example. The cheap and the middle priced TV both give an equal amount of stress reduction, negating the point of buying the more expensive TV. The other part which makes no sense at all is you have to pay for your own gas and vehicle repairs. I could understand repairs to a point, as you should be punished somehow for wrecking a squad car, but fuel? That makes no sense. Require fill-ups, sure. But no cop pays for fuel from his own pocket.The controls are functional, but again need thought out a little better. For instance, when ordering a suspect to stop, you have to use the ""C"" key. If you have your gun out, in order to fire, you first have to ""aim"" with a right click. I would remove the ""aim"" portion (since you should already be aiming if your gun is out) and bind the command function to the right click, so you can give orders quickly and still be prepared to shoot. Again, not a big issue, just an annoyance.So what is good about this game? All of it. It's a hell of a concept, with many underlying systems which make it all work well together. It's not perfect and it's a buggy mess, but it does have a certain allure and charm. The different styles of cruisers are really cool. Thee are several customization options once rank 3 is unlocked, including rims, paint scheme, lightbar type, and colors of each side on the lightbar. Once again, it needs more, but it really is a cool start.The missions can be repetative, but the constant stress of responding to a call and not knowing what you're walking into is really well captured. Sometimes it ends in a gunfight, sometimes they run then turn and shoot at you, and sometimes they just surrender or you really have to work at identifying which person is the right suspect. Again, it has it's flaws, but has potential. The biggest complaint I have is that there is always a suspect somewhere when given a call. It would be nice to occasionally find out no crime was actually comitted, but that would require a much more in-depth investigation system which I doubt this game would be capable of pulling off.Sometimes drivers pull over, sometimes a chase ensues, sometimes they bail and run on foot. Again, you never know what you will get. I can't commend this game well enough at mixing in the unknown to every contact with a car or suspect. It really is a good mix and keeps the game entertaining.If you want a perfect, AAA game with minimal bugs, tons of content, and bleeding edge graphics, then skip this title. However, if you enjoy finding hidden gems that might be a little rough around the edges, then definately give this one a shot. Have realistic expectations of what teh game is and is not and you will find it really enjoyable.Also, if you have younger children that are always fascinated with police, fire and ambulance vehicle every time they see one, then play this with them. There is no gorey bloody deaths, and while there is the occasional shootout, you still have to call an ambulance for the ""bad guy"" and be the good guy. For some with small children, it can be a good option instead of GTA and stealing cop cars."
