76561197962301472,Not Recommended,318220,21815518,"Posted: 13 March, 2016",all,[WB] MR PANTS,"So, when I saw this game, I thought it was going to be like Police Quest and be a police sim with some kind of accuracy about it.However, it's a good deal more like GTA from the police perspective.Honestly, I think the thing that throws me off the most is the dialog.  A lot of what's said from dispatch, or the written text, is odd and strikes me as non-English speakers who've never watched Cops trying to write dialog.  I would expect less ""There's a murderer on the loose"" and more ""Shots fired; civilian casualties"" or ""Armed suspect reported"" or the like.  Google searches reveal that the dialog used to be even worse, so this is *after improvement*.There isn't much polish; the little things will constantly eat at you.  Like, trying to back up your squad car feels clunky, or having it slide backwards down a hill when it's parked (which I guess is fixed in the latest patch).  You basically harass and pull over random people to try and make your quotas, with only a few traffic violations being ""externally visible"".  I will say I was really impressed when, at night, I could actually see people with their headlights broken and ticket them for it.  That was cool, I'll give them that!You can't pull people over for running lights, you can't issue tickets for accidents.  The game doesn't seem to care if you, yourself, drive recklessly and there doesn't seem to be a penalty for damaging innocent cars.  Scarface: The World Is Yours had better traffic law mechanics.  I couldn't even pull over a truck that ran a light, then rammed into a street light and blocked an intersection.And finally, the weather; when it started raining, the sound of the storm was really overwhelming and irritating.  And it was raining inside the police station, which was great.  In my house, at least it wasn't raining in there but it was still equally loud as outside.  Really obnoxious.One of the things that made Police Quest cool was they actually hired law enforcement folks to help design the game.  I'd love these guys to take another shot at this game, with Enforcer 2, and actually hire a cop to help them make it.  Despite all my problems with this game, I really want to love it, and I really tried to, so please try again."
